[[File:Logo MCRL.png|thumb|right|200px|Group's logo.]]The '''Free Costa Rica Movement''' (''Movimiento Costa Rica Libre'') was a [[far-right]] [[anti-Communist]] and [[ultra-Conservative]] political association in [[Costa Rica]].<ref name="Jongman">{{cite book|last1=Jongman|first1=Albert J.|title=Political Terrorism: A New Guide To Actors, Authors, Concepts, Data Bases|url=https://books.google.co.cr/books?id=NgDks1hUjhMC&pg=PA527&lpg=PA527&dq=free+costa+rica+movement&source=bl&ots=kYEFCIRYFe&sig=xsxAc0RNHCZW1Uj6bGPNxiZgkuI&hl=es&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=free%20costa%20rica%20movement&f=false|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="Long">{{cite news|last1=Long|first1=William|title=Right-Wingers Glare Across Border : Anti-Sandinista Feelings Intensifying in Costa Rica|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-07-06/news/mn-9462_1_northern-costa-rica|accessdate=April 13, 2016|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=July 6, 1985}}</ref> The group was founded in 1961 as Nationalist Movement (''Movimiento Nacionalista''). Some of its more noticeable actions were during neighboring [[Nicaragua]]’s [[Sandinista Revolution|Sandinista government]] in the 80s, as the group was strongly anti-Sandinista and considered Sandinista Nicaragua a treat to Costa Rica.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sandoval|first1=Carlos|title=Threatening Others: Nicaraguans and the Formation of National Identities in Costa Rica|url=https://books.google.co.cr/books?id=9PpdBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> The group attacked Nicaragua’s embassy in 1981.<ref name="Jongman"/> Besides the [[FSLN]], the group was also enemy of several Costa Rican [[left-wing]] parties like [[United People (Costa Rica)|United People]] and several farmers and workers organizations.<ref name="Long"/> It was also a member of the [[World Anti-Communist League]].

