{{Expand section|1=more depth to discussion|section=1|date=November 2018|small=no|talksection=Police legitimacy}}
'''Police legitimacy''' is the extent to which members of the public view the [[police]] as legitimate, often measured in terms of the public's willingness to obey and cooperate with the police. Police legitimacy is linked to the degree of public support for, and cooperation with, the police's efforts to fight crime.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199843886.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199843886-e-017 | title=Police Legitimacy | work=The Oxford Handbook of Police and Policing | date=April 2014 | accessdate=24 April 2017 | author=Tankebe, Justice}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tyler|first1=Tom R.|title=Enhancing Police Legitimacy|journal=The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science|date=1 May 2004|volume=593|issue=1|pages=84–99|doi=10.1177/0002716203262627}}</ref> If police lose their legitimacy, it can compromise their ability and authority to work effectively.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nij.gov/topics/law-enforcement/legitimacy/Pages/welcome.aspx | title=Race, Trust and Police Legitimacy|publisher=[[National Institute of Justice]]| accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>
People who experience more [[procedural justice]] in police encounters view the police as more legitimate.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://moritzlaw.osu.edu/osjcl/Articles/Volume6_1/Tyler-Fagan-PDF.pdf | title=Legitimacy and Cooperation: Why Do People Help the Police Fight Crime in Their Communities? | author=Tyler, Tom; Fagan, Jeffrey | journal=Ohio State Journal of Criminal Law | year=2008 | issue=6}}</ref> In contrast, order maintenance policing and widespread street stops appear to reduce police legitimacy among young men.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gau|first1=Jacinta M.|last2=Brunson|first2=Rod K.|title=Procedural Justice and Order Maintenance Policing: A Study of Inner‐City Young Men’s Perceptions of Police Legitimacy|journal=Justice Quarterly|date=April 2010|volume=27|issue=2|pages=255–279|doi=10.1080/07418820902763889}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tyler|first1=Tom R.|last2=Fagan|first2=Jeffrey|last3=Geller|first3=Amanda|title=Street Stops and Police Legitimacy: Teachable Moments in Young Urban Men's Legal Socialization|journal=Journal of Empirical Legal Studies|date=December 2014|volume=11|issue=4|pages=751–785|doi=10.1111/jels.12055}}</ref>
